  "script": "A tornado near Chicago? Storms tore across the Chicago suburbs this week, and near Huntley, Illinois a funnel actually touched down — video caught debris getting ripped up and spun through the air. Towns like Streamwood, Bartlett, and Hanover Park got hammered with straight-line winds that snapped trees and tore off roofs. This is the part of a storm where seconds matter: the sky goes still, then green, then the wind hits like a wall. Forecasters had warned people to get to a basement and stay there. A tornado in the suburbs doesn't care about your fence or your car. So when the funnel is half a mile away, where do you actually go?",
